  "prompt": "What is the universal grammar theory?",
  "response": "The Universal Grammar (UG) theory is a linguistic concept primarily developed by Noam Chomsky in the 1950s. The key points of this theory include:\n\n1. Core Premise:\n- All humans are born with an innate, biological capacity for language learning\n- There is a common set of linguistic principles that underlie all human languages\n\n2. Key Features:\n- Humans have a \"language acquisition device\" in their brain\n- Children can learn any language they are exposed to during a critical period\n- Basic grammatical structures are hardwired and universal across languages\n\n3. Main Arguments:\n- Children acquire language too quickly and easily to learn purely through imitation\n- Despite limited linguistic input, children can generate complex, novel sentences\n- There are fundamental grammatical similarities across diverse languages\n\n4. Linguistic Universals:\n- All languages have basic structural elements like nouns and verbs\n- Languages share fundamental syntactic rules and principles\n- There are common constraints on how languages can be structured\n\n5. Theoretical Implications:\n- Language is a unique human cognitive capability\n- Biological factors play a significant role in language development\n- Grammar is not entirely learned, but partially predetermined\n\nWhile influential, the Universal Grammar theory remains controversial and has been challenged by alternative linguistic and cognitive theories.",
